    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-12-27T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-12-27T23:00:00-05:00" n="850"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d850">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.00/555: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-12-28T13:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 28, 1935—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 28—2:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>254. Count Makino, Lord Keeper of the Privy Seal, has resigned and was replaced
                    by Viscount Saito on the afternoon of December 26. The reason given for the
                    change was Makino’s ill health. From all that the Embassy has been able to
                    learn, the reason given is the true one. Count Makino has been in poor health
                    for some months.</p>
                <p>The appointment of Viscount Saito, formerly Prime Minister, indicates that there
                    are likely to be no new influences affecting the throne in the near future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
